                <head>
                    <title>Toward a Wikipedia model of drug discovery</title>
                <?php include_once 'Elemental/header.php'; ?><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><br><br><h5> This article is reformatted from originally published at <a href="https://readplaintext.com/toward-a-wikipedia-model-of-drug-discovery-79a2c7bcf88c"><strong>TDS(Towards Data Science)</strong></a></h5></br><h5> <a href="https://medium.com/@elidourado?source=post_page-----79a2c7bcf88c--------------------------------">Author : Eli Dourado</a> </h5></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content4 cid-tt5SM2WLsM" id="content4-2" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
            <div class="container">
                <div class="row justify-content-center">
                    <div class="title col-md-12 col-lg-9">
                        <h3 class="mbr-section-title mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-2">
                            <strong>Toward a Wikipedia model of drug discovery</h3></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5 text-muted">How Apple’s ResearchKit — or something like it — can democratize our search for new medical treatments.</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">As the world tuned in to see Apple reveal its new Watch this week, the company made another announcement that may be far more consequential in the long run. With <a href="http://www.apple.com/researchkit/" target="_self">ResearchKit</a>, Apple’s new open source software framework for medical research apps, Cupertino is dipping <a href="https://developer.apple.com/healthkit/" target="_self">another toe</a> into healthcare, one of the most dysfunctional sectors of the economy. This is unmistakably good news, for the greater the dysfunction of the incumbent industry, the larger the social gains from disruption.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">While Apple’s ResearchKit announcement contained some of the company’s characteristically grandiose marketing language, it was also in a way quite modest. Apple envisions its new framework being used primarily by the existing medical research establishment in ways that are not altogether different from the status quo. Instead of collecting data from subjects every 3 months, researchers will collect data every 3 hours. Instead of collecting data from 100 subjects, they will collect data from 100,000.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">This will make medical research better and cheaper, but the real gains from ResearchKit’s simpler data collection will come when it is paired with other technologies that are on the way. Innovations in medical testing, 3D printing, and data analysis will combine with smartphone-based data collection to revolutionize the way we do medical research, with lower costs and better outcomes.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:10%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 100px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:200/format:webp/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg 200w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 100px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:200/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg 200w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/100/1*LIASvGQPoNUaQcX-ezI46w.jpeg"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">Eroom’s Law</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Not only does everyone know about Moore’s Law nowadays, they feel its effect directly every time they upgrade their iPhones. It doesn’t take a hardcore techie to understand that “the back half of the chessboard” is special, that exponential processes are, to paraphrase an Einstein imposter, the most powerful forces in the universe.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Sometimes those powerful forces are socially and economically beneficial, as when computer processor complexity doubles every two years. But not all exponential processes are so kind. Take a gander at <strong>Eroom’s Law</strong> (<em>Eroom </em>is <em>Moore </em>backwards): since 1950, the number of drugs approved per billion dollars in R&D spending has halved every 9 years, adjusted for inflation.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/1*VMDeRe9pmZcIlaEm575-Hg.jpeg"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">From Jack W. Scannell, Alex Blanckley, Helen Boldon & Brian Warrington, “<a href="http://www.nature.com/nrd/journal/v11/n3/full/nrd3681.html" target="_self">Diagnosing the decline in pharmaceutical R&D efficiency</a>,” <em>Nature Reviews Drug Discovery 11</em>, 191–200 (March 2012).</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The 80-fold decline in the efficiency of drug discovery is all the more striking when you consider that many of the inputs to pharmaceutical research and development have <em>benefited</em> from Moore’s Law. As the authors who <a href="http://www.nature.com/nrd/journal/v11/n3/full/nrd3681.html" target="_self">coined the term</a> note,</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">Eroom’s Law indicates that powerful forces have outweighed scientific, technical and managerial improvements over the past 60 years, and/or that some of the improvements have been less ‘improving’ than commonly thought. <mark>The more positive anyone is about the past several decades of progress, the more negative they should be about the strength of countervailing forces</mark> [emphasis added].</p></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">We are missing thousands of drugs; millions of people have suffered unnecessarily or gone to early deaths because those drugs were not discovered. The current model of drug discovery — in which companies fund research, patent molecules, conduct clinical trials, and seek approval from regulators — is broken. It’s time to seek an alternative.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
